title="Chris Purdy">Chris Purdy</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>In the previous iteration of the proof system, we just took contexts as <fr:em>sets</fr:em> of formulae. This is problematic from a proof reduction point of view. Consider implication reduction (cut-elimination):
  
  <html:center
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:resource
hash="1eaa8ad1cd17bb2d77a51d5ab2260d60"><fr:resource-content><fr:img
src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source
type="latex"
part="preamble"><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }
  ]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source
type="latex"
part="body"><![CDATA[
    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma , \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi  \Rightarrow  \psi $}
      \AxiomC {$\Pi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \phi $}
      \BinaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}
    $\ \ \rightsquigarrow $
    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma [\Pi  / \phi ]$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:center>

  Intuitively <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma [\Pi  / \phi ]]]></fr:tex> is defined as "remove <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> from the context everywhere in the sub-proof <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>, and replace axioms for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Pi ]]></fr:tex>". However, what happens if there is already <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi  \in  \Gamma ]]></fr:tex>? We don't know whether the "occurence" of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> that is derived from an axiom rule in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is the one previously in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> or not - the same issue persists if we take contexts as multi-sets.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:link
type="external"
href="https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~fp/courses/15317-f17/lectures/02-natded.pdf">Pfenning's notes on natural deduction</fr:link> deal with this by using hypotheses labelled with variables, with the axiom and implication introduction rules specifying the variable name of the hypothesis they discharge/introduce. In traditional natural deduction systems, essentially the same approach is taken, but with a "de Bruijn index" approach instead of variable labels. Taking one of these approaches makes it very clear during <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Rightarrow ]]></fr:tex>-reduction which hypotheses is being "eliminated" from the context.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
